<dl id="n54108c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54108c">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54108c"> 108(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> green mantle <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54108c"><li>FW 131.21 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n54108c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n54108c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54108c">MS BL 47476a-220</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:463 <a name="fad8" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad8.htm#n54108c">Draft: I.6&sect;1.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Rumors of the plot <font color="green">[by the Kuraysh]</font> having reached Mohammed, he escaped from the back of his house, and took refuge with his friend Abu Bakr. Meanwhile Ali laid himself down on the Prophet&apos;s bed, wrapped in his <mark>green mantle</mark>, to deceive any of the enemy who might chance to look in, thus allowing Mohammed time to get safely away. <small> Edith Holland, <a name="EHSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EHSM"><cite title="source">The Story of Mohammed</cite></a> (1914) 80</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
